Predictive models¶

Based on the knowledge gained in the explanatory section, we wish to investigate the following questions:

  • Can I predict if my flight will be cancelled?
  • Can I predict if my flight will arrive late?

Both these questions can add value to both the customers, airlines and airports. Being able to predict cancelled flights will allow for better utilization of resources in an airport and allocation of planes. The customer will be able to stay home in case of a cancelled flight.

With respect to delays, we only focus on arrivals, mainly for the sake of brevity. However, it should be noted that attemps were made to predict departure delays, which showed results similar to arrival delays. This makes sense with respect to the correlation between them, as seen in the exploratory notebook.

The delays can add value in the same terms of optimization problems for airports and customers. Allocation of planes can be optimized and customer's arrival time to the airport.

We will apply three machine learning classifiers:

  • Multi-layer Perceptrons
  • Logistic Regression
  • XGBoost

Developing and evaluating the models will make use of cross validation techniques, grid search, train test splits and downsampling to deal with the class imbalance problem.

In [195]:
df19 = pd.read_csv("Jan_2019_ontime_weather_imputed_clean.csv")
df20 = pd.read_csv("Jan_2020_ontime_weather_imputed_clean.csv")

In the dataset, there are way more non cancellations and delays than actual cancellations and delays. The cost of telling the client that they do not have to show up at the airport, because their flight is cancelled, but the flight is actually not cancelled (false positive) is high, due to them losing all the money they spent on the ticket. For false negatives, the cost is not as high, as the client will just find another plane with reimbursement.

Based on this, we choose the f1 score as a metric, which describes how well a model performs with respect to recall and precision. Rather than only how well it predicts the true cases which the accuracy measures. We could also choose the roc area as a metric, but f1 proved generally better results.

Even though cancellations would have a higher business impact, the prediction of delays are also of business interest, more specially for the airlines and their customer excelence, that's why we will also set as target the delays.

Data processing¶

We will split the data into a training set to train the models on, a validation set to validate the hyperparameters and finally a test set to see the performance of the model on unseen data.

Since we have data for both 2019 and 2020, we will use the 2019 data for training and validation, and the 2020 data for testing. This way, we can show that the models are able to predict cancellations and delays in the future.

As some models are sensitive to the scale of continuous features, we will standardize the features as well.

We define a general function to make it easier to change properties of training data, such as features

In [196]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder, StandardScaler
In [197]:
# Getting train test splits
def get_split(df, features, target, cat_cols=None, scale_cols=None, should_split=True):
    X = df[features]
    y = df[target]
    
    # One hot encode
    if cat_cols:
        cat_vars = df[cat_cols]

        enc = OneHotEncoder().fit(cat_vars)

        encoded_matrix = enc.transform(cat_vars)

        encoded_df = pd.DataFrame(encoded_matrix.toarray(), index=cat_vars.index, columns=enc.get_feature_names(cat_vars.columns.tolist()))
        
        X = pd.concat([X.drop(cat_cols, axis=1), encoded_df], axis=1)
    
    # Split
    # We stratify on our target (Cancellations) to get the same proportions of positive and negative cancellations
    X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X, y, stratify=y)
    
    # Scale
    if scale_cols:  
        sc = StandardScaler().fit(X_train[scale_cols])
        X_train[scale_cols] = sc.transform(X_train[scale_cols])
        X_val[scale_cols] = sc.transform(X_val[scale_cols])
    
    if should_split:
        return X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val
    else:
        return X_train.append(X_val), y_train.append(y_val)
In [198]:
def align_columns(X_test, X_train):
    missing_cols = set(X_train.columns).difference(set(X_test.columns))
    missing_cols2 = set(X_test.columns).difference(set(X_train.columns))

    if len(missing_cols) > 0:
        print('Columns missing from test set')
        print(missing_cols)
        X_test[list(missing_cols)] = 0

    if len(missing_cols2) > 0:
        print('Columns missing from train set')
        print(missing_cols2)
        X_test = X_test.drop(missing_cols2, axis=1)
    
    if len(missing_cols) + len(missing_cols2) == 0:
        print('Columns already match')
    
    return X_test

Utility functions¶

We define some functions to help evaluate the models more easily

In [24]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.metrics import auc, accuracy_score, roc_curve, confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score, recall_score, precision_score, roc_auc_score
In [25]:
# Define evaluation
def evaluate_model(y_true, y_pred):
    print('F1 score', f1_score(y_true, y_pred))
    print('Recall', recall_score(y_true, y_pred))
    print('Precision', precision_score(y_true, y_pred))
    print('Accuracy', accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred))

def plot_roc(y_true, probs):
    """
    https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/model_selection/plot_roc.html
    """
    fpr = dict()
    tpr = dict()
    roc_auc = dict()

    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_true, probs)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

    plt.figure()
    lw = 2
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange',
             lw=lw, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=lw, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()
    
def plot_confusion(y_true, y_pred):
    cf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, normalize='all')
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))
    
    cf = pd.DataFrame(cf_matrix)
    cf.index.name = 'Actual'
    cf.columns.name = 'Predicted'
    
    sns.heatmap(cf, annot=True, fmt='.2%')
    plt.show()

Imbalanced vs Balanced Data¶

The nature of our data is clearly imbalanced, to see the impact of that we performed a prelimary analysis on whether which kind of data our models could predict better. The parameters for this prelimary analysis were chosen through trial and error and intuition. However, we will perform hyperparameter tuning to find the optimal set.

Conclusion¶

The models were capable of performing very well on the train and validation dataset, being the 2019 data.

For predicting flight cancellations, the best performing model turned out to be XGBoost, with an area under the ROC curve of 0.88 and F1 score of 0.76.

For predicting flight delays, the best performing model turned out to be XGBoost, with an area under the ROC curve of 0.71 and F1 score of 0.60.

However... the models were rendered useless when testing on the test data from 2020. Following the insights gained from the exploratory analysis, this makes sense. In January 2019, the US government and two snow storms caused the airports to shut down.

We are therefore seeing the example of correlation vs causality in terms of the models finding the correlation in 2019, but not the cause behind the cancellations or delays, as it performs poorly on the test data. Even if it was provided with the weather data as features.

It was therefore not possible to predict either cancellations or delays.

Future work¶

To improve the predictive models one could take a few approaches.

First we discussed the possiblity of adding more data, such as activity of airports (could be derived) and getting the expected departure and arrival times (strange that it wasn't present in the first place). These features could potentially have better correlation with the targets.

Moreover, one could remove the detected anomalies from the dataset, such as the snowstorms and shutdown of airports. This will make the dataset more general and hopefully improve the models ability to explain cause and not correlation.

Finally, one could merge the two datasets, 2019 and 2020, but this might cause issues when predicting for 2021..
